NeverthelesS, the Parthian kings generally made no scruple os inter· posing from time to time in Armenia 3² in which, from the appointment of Tigranes 11 in 734, 13.c. 20, we have for nearly forty years an almost continuone history of interference and intrigue, resulting in revolution and anarchy. The account of these vicissitudes can be read as related in its place by Tacitus ⁸ ; but it will be well to compare here the alternatives open to Rome in dealing with this Asghanistan of the ancient world.

Subsequent experience may be taken generally to have shown that a policy of complete non-interference would have been best, and that the efforts os Rome were sar more needed in extending and consolidating the empire in other quarters3 but Augustus could not slight the traditions os the Republic, or allow it to be said that even an imaginary limit of the empire had receded under him.
